n his later, more well-known writings. Collected here, these previously unpublished texts reveal a Foucault who undertakes an analysis of language and experience detached from their historical constraints. Three issues predominate: the experience of madness across societies; madness and language in Artaud, Roussel, and Baroque theater; and structuralist literary criticism. Not only do these texts pursue concepts unique to this period such as the “extra-linguistic,” but they also reveal a far more complex relationship between structuralism and Foucault than has typically been acknowledged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEuropean literaturexThemes, motives. 0aMental illness in literature. 0aMental illnessxPhilosophy. 0aMental illnessxSocial aspects. 0aStructuralism (Literary analysis) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBononno, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFruchaud, Henri-Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLorenzini, Daniele, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRevel, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226774978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226774978/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles